{"title_page": "Quentin Edwards", "text_new": "'''Quentin Tytler Edwards''' [[Queens Counsel|QC]] (1925\u20132010) was a British [[barrister]] and [[Circuit judge (England and Wales)|circuit judge]].\n\n==Early life==\nEdwards was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]],<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/his-honour-quentin-edwards-nzbkhpc6p76 \u201dHis Honour Quentin Edwards\u201d] (obituary) in ''[[The Times]]'', 31 October 2010, accessed 25 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\nthe son of a shipbroker, and had an exotic childhood there. While he was at [[Bradfield College]], he struck up a friendship with [[John Mortimer]], who became infatuated with him, leading to passionate letters from Mortimer. These resulted in Edwards being expelled from Bradfield, at the age of seventeen, during the Second World War. He then worked on a farm and in a factory before joining the [[Royal Navy]] in 1943.<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Career==\nEdwards left the Navy in 1946 and began to read law at the [[Middle Temple]]. He was [[called to the bar]] from there in 1948 and became a serious scholar of [[ecclesiastical law]].<ref name=hill/> He was a [[bencher]] of his inn before being appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]].<ref name=times/> In December 1974, he was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]],<ref>''[[The London Gazette]]'', 13 December 1974, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46430/page/12745/data.pdf p. 12745]</ref> and \nin 1982 was appointed as a circuit judge on the south eastern circuit.<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Vol. 126 (The Journal, 1982), p. 516: \u201cMr Quentin Tytler Edwards QC has been appointed a circuit judge and assigned to the south eastern circuit.\u201d</ref> He continued in that post for fifteen years, and was also [[Chancellor (ecclesiastical)|Chancellor]] of the [[diocese]]s of [[diocese of Blackburn|Blackburn]] and [[diocese of Chichester|Chichester]].<ref name=times/>\n\n==Private life==\nIn 1948, Edwards married Barbara Guthrie,<ref>\u201cEdwards Quentin T, Guthrie\t Barbara M, Kensington 5c 2285\u201d in ''General Index to Marriages in England and Wales'', 1948</ref> on the day after he had been called to the bar. They had two sons and a daughter. His wife died in 2006.<ref name=hill>[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]], [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/ecclej13&div=48&id=&page= \u201cHis Honour Quentin Edwards QC (1925\u20132010)\u201d] in ''Ecclesiastical Law Journal'' (2010)</ref>\n''[[The Times]]'' said of Edwards in an obituary that he was a dandy and a [[P. G. Wodehouse|Wodehouse-style]] figure,  \u201cinstantly recognisable with his abundant sidewhiskers, half-moon spectacles and rosy cheeks\u201d, and that he loved to attend race meetings, especially Ascot, Newmarket, Cheltenham, and the dog races in Hackney. In his ecclesiastical role, he would visit churches in the morning and then spend an afternoon at the races.<ref name=times/>\n[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]] recalled that Edwards was \u201ca stickler for propriety and good manners... quixotic, urbane, and wickedly amusing... occasionally irascible.\u201d<ref name=hill/>\n\nHe lived in [[Highgate]], [[North London]], for fifty years and became a pillar of the community there.<ref name=times/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English judges]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bradfield College]]\n[[Category:People from Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "'''Quentin Tytler Edwards''' [[Queens Counsel|QC]] (1925\u20132010) was a British [[barrister]] and [[Circuit judge (England and Wales)|circuit judge]].\n\n==Early life==\nEdwards was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]],<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/his-honour-quentin-edwards-nzbkhpc6p76 \u201dHis Honour Quentin Edwards\u201d] (obituary) in ''[[The Times]]'', 31 October 2010, accessed 25 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\nthe son of a shipbroker, and had an exotic childhood there. While he was at [[Bradfield College]], he struck up a friendship with [[John Mortimer]], who became infatuated with him, leading to passionate letters from Mortimer. These resulted in Edwards being expelled from Bradfield, at the age of seventeen, during the Second World War. He then worked on a farm and a factory before joining the [[Royal Navy]] in 1943.<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Career==\nEdwards left the Navy in 1946 and began to read law at the [[Middle Temple]]. He was [[called to the bar]] from there in 1948 and became a serious scholar of [[ecclesiastical law]].<ref name=hill/> He was a [[bencher]] of his inn before being appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]].<ref name=times/> In December 1974, he was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]],<ref>''[[The London Gazette]]'', 13 December 1974, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46430/page/12745/data.pdf p. 12745]</ref> and \nin 1982 was appointed as a circuit judge on the south eastern circuit.<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Vol. 126 (The Journal, 1982), p. 516: \u201cMr Quentin Tytler Edwards QC has been appointed a circuit judge and assigned to the south eastern circuit.\u201d</ref> He continued in that post for fifteen years, and was also [[Chancellor (ecclesiastical)|Chancellor]] of the [[diocese]]s of [[diocese of Blackburn|Blackburn]] and [[diocese of Chichester|Chichester]].<ref name=times/>\n\n==Private life==\nIn 1948, Edwards married Barbara Guthrie,<ref>\u201cEdwards Quentin T, Guthrie\t Barbara M, Kensington 5c 2285\u201d in ''General Index to Marriages in England and Wales'', 1948</ref> on the day after he had been called to the bar. They had two sons and a daughter. His wife died in 2006.<ref name=hill>[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]], [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/ecclej13&div=48&id=&page= \u201cHis Honour Quentin Edwards QC (1925\u20132010)\u201d] in ''Ecclesiastical Law Journal'' (2010)</ref>\n''[[The Times]]'' said of Edwards in an obituary that he was a dandy and a [[P. G. Wodehouse|Wodehouse-style]] figure,  \u201cinstantly recognisable with his abundant sidewhiskers, half-moon spectacles and rosy cheeks\u201d, and that he loved to attend race meetings, especially Ascot, Newmarket, Cheltenham, and the dog races in Hackney. In his ecclesiastical role, he would visit churches in the morning and then spend an afternoon at the races.<ref name=times/>\n[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]] recalled that Edwards was \u201ca stickler for propriety and good manners... quixotic, urbane, and wickedly amusing... occasionally irascible.\u201d<ref name=hill/>\n\nHe lived in [[Highgate]], [[North London]], for fifty years and became a pillar of the community there.<ref name=times/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English judges]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bradfield College]]\n[[Category:People from Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quentin_Edwards"}
{"title_page": "2019 Kentucky Wildcats football team", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 University of Kentucky football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=2019\n  |team=Kentucky Wildcats\n  |sport=football\n  |image=Kentucky Wildcats logo.svg\n  |image_size=150px\n  |conference=Southeastern Conference\n  |short_conf=SEC\n  |division=Eastern Division\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=\n  |CFPRank=\n  |record = 8\u20135\n  |conf_record = 3\u20135\n  |head_coach=[[Mark Stoops]]\n  |hc_year=7th\n  |off_coach = Eddie Gran\n  |oc_year =4th\n  |cooff_coach1 = Darin Hinshaw\n  |cooc1_year =4th\n  |def_coach= Brad White (1st season)<ref name=\"Brad White\">{{Cite web|url=https://ukathletics.com/sports/football/roster/coaches/brad-white/1727|title=Brad White - Football Coach|website=University of Kentucky Athletics}}</ref>\n | bowl = [[2019 Belk Bowl|Belk Bowl]]\n | bowl_result = W 37\u201330 vs. [[2019 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]]\n| champion = Belk Bowl champion\n  |stadium=[[Kroger Field]]<br>(Capacity: 61,000)\n}}\n{{2019 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2019 Kentucky Wildcats football team''' represented the [[University of Kentucky]] in the [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Wildcats played their home games at [[Kroger Field]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]], and competed in the East Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). They were led by seventh-year head coach [[Mark Stoops]].\n\n==Preseason==\n===SEC preseason poll===\nThe 2019 SEC Media Days were held July 15\u201318 in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. In the preseason media poll, Kentucky was projected to finish in sixth in the East Division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.secsports.com/article/27221515/media-predicts-alabama-win-2019-sec-championship|title=Media predicts Alabama to win 2019 SEC Championship|date=July 19, 2019|website=SECSports.com|publisher=Southeastern Conference}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"display: inline-table;\"\n|align=\"center\" Colsp