A Cup|2003\u201304]]\n| [[UEFA Cup]]\n| [[2003\u201304 UEFA Cup#Qualifying round|QR]]\n| align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[U.D. Leiria|Uni\u00e3o de Leiria]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20131\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20135\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2\u20136'''\n|-\n| [[2017-18 UEFA Europa League|2017\u201318]]\n| [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League#First qualifying round|1QR]]\n| align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|Norway}} [[FK Haugesund|Haugesund]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20137\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''0\u20137'''\n|-\n| |[[2018\u201319 UEFA Europa League|2018\u201319]]\n| |[[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2018\u201319 UEFA Europa League#First qualifying round|1QR]]\n| align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|Serbia}} [[FK Spartak Subotica]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20132\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1\u20133'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Current squad==\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|nat=NIR|pos=GK|name=Chris Johns|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 2|nat=NIR|pos=DF|name=Lyndon Kane|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|nat=IRE|pos=DF|name=Adam Mullan|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|nat=NIR|pos=DF|name=Aaron Canning|other=}} \n{{Fs player|no= 5|nat=NIR|pos=DF|name=Stephen Douglas|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=Aaron Jarvis|other=}} \n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=IRE|pos=MF|name=Ben Doherty|other=}} \n{{Fs player|no= 8|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=Stephen Lowry|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=James McLaughlin|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=[[Eoin Bradley]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=[[Josh Carson]]|other=}}\n{{fs mid}} \n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=NIR|pos=DF|name=Gareth McConaghie|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=IRE|pos=DF|name=Stephen O'Donnell|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=Ian Parkhill|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name= Jamie Glackin|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=IRE|pos=DF|name=Aaron Traynor|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=Alexander Gawne|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=Emmett McGuckin|other=}} \n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=LTU|pos=FW|name=Nedas Maciulaitis|other=}} \n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=Andrew Whiteside|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=NIR|pos=GK|name=Martin Gallagher|other=}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Non-playing staff==\n*President: Andy Magowan\n*Chairman: Colin McKendry\n*Vice Chairman: Raymond Smyth\n*General Manager: Stevie McCann\n*Matchday Secretary: Hunter McClelland\n*Chaplain: Reverend Robert McMullan\n*Assistant Manager: Trevor McKendry\n*First Team Coach: William Murphy\n*Treasurer: Colin McKendry\n\n==Managerial history==\n*{{flagicon|Scotland}} [[Jock McIntyre]] (1929 \u2013 1931)\n*{{flagicon|Scotland}} [[Willie Buchan]] (1953 \u2013 1954)\n*Bertie Peacock (1961-1974)\n*Ivan Murray/Johnny McCurdy  (1974-1978)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Des Dickson (footballer, born 1948)|Des Dickson]] (July 1981 \u2013 June 1983)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Kenny Shiels]]\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Jim Platt]] (1985\u20131991)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Marty Quinn (footballer)|Marty Quinn]] (Oct 1999 \u2013 May 8 2008)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}}David Platt (2008 - 2011)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} Aidy McLaughlin ''(interim)'' (30 Jan 2011 \u2013 5 Feb 2011)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Oran Kearney]] (5 Feb 2011 \u2013 6 Sep 2018)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Rodney McAree]] (14 Sep 2018 \u2013 10 May 2019)\n*{{flagicon|Northern Ireland}} [[Oran Kearney]] (3 July 2019 \u2013 )\n\n==Honours==\n===Senior honours===\n*'''[[IFA Premiership|Irish League]]: 1'''\n**[[1973\u201374 Irish League|1973\u201374]]\n*'''[[Irish Cup]]: 6'''\n**1964\u201365, 1971\u201372, 1974\u201375, [[1976\u201377 Irish Cup|1976\u201377]], [[2002\u201303 Irish Cup|2002\u201303]], [[2017-18 Irish Cup|2017-18]]\n*'''[[Irish League Cup]]: 2'''\n**[[1987\u201388 Irish League Cup|1987\u201388]] , 2019-20.\n*'''[[City Cup (Northern Ireland)|City Cup]]: 2'''\n**1953\u201354, 1968\u201369\n*'''[[Gold Cup (Northern Ireland)|Gold Cup]]: 4'''\n**1932, 1958, 1969, 1975\n*'''[[Ulster Cup]]: 8'''\n**1965\u201366, 1968\u201369, 1969\u201370, 1972\u201373, 1975\u201376, 1985\u201386, 1986\u201387, 1996\u201397\n*'''[[Top Four Cup (Northern Ireland)|Top Four Cup]]'''\n**1968\u201369\n*'''[[North West Senior Cup]]: 21'''\n**1952\u201353\u2020, 1954\u201355, 1955\u201356, 1957\u201358, 1958\u201359, 1960\u201361, 1964\u201365, 1967\u201368, 1980\u201381, 1981\u201382, 1982\u201383, 1987\u201388, 1988\u201389, 1991\u201392, 1994\u201395, 2001\u201302, 2003\u201304 2005\u201306, 2007\u201308, 2009\u201310, 2012\u201313\n*'''[[IFA Premiership|Irish League First Division]]: 1'''\n**1995\u201396\n*'''[[Blaxnit Cup]]: 2'''\n**1968\u201369, 1969\u201370\n*'''[[Irish News Cup]]: 1'''\n**1995\u201396\n\n<small>\u2020 Won by Coleraine Reserves</small>\n\n===Intermediate honours===\n*'''[[Irish Intermediate Cup]]: 2'''\n**1964\u201365\u2020, 1968\u201369\u2020\n*'''[[George Wilson Cup]]: 4'''\n**1954\u201355\u2020, 1985\u201386\u2020, 1991\u201392\u2020, 1995\u201396\u2020\n*'''[[Craig Memorial Cup]]: 3'''\n**1984\u201385\u2020, 1986\u201387\u2020, 2013\u201314\u2020\n\n<small>\u2020 Won by Coleraine Reserves</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.colerainefc.com/ Official Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121018052349/http://home.online.no/~smogols/ifcp/clubs/coleraine/clubcoleraine.htm Coleraine Statistics and Results at the Irish Football Club Project]\n\n{{Football in Northern Ireland}}\n{{NIFL league}}\n\n[[Category:Coleraine F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1927]]\n[[Category:Coleraine]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership clubs]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs in County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=December 2016}}\n{{One source|date=March 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Coleraine\n| image = Coleraine FC.svg\n| upright = 0.75\n| alt = Logo\n| fullname = Coleraine Football Club\n| nickname = The Bannsiders\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1927|6}}\n| ground = [[The Showgrounds (Coleraine)|The Showgrounds]]\n| captain = Will Carrigan\n| chairman = Scott Cooke\n| manager = [[Oran Kearney]]\n| league = [[NIFL Premiership]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 NIFL Premiership|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[NIFL Premiership]], 6th\n| current = 2019\u201320 NIFL Premiership\n| website = https://colerainefc.com/\n| pattern_la1 = _coleraine1718h\n| pattern_b1 = _coleraine1718h\n| pattern_ra1 = _coleraine1718h\n| pattern_sh1 = _coleraine1718h\n| pattern_so1 = _coleraine1718h\n| leftarm1 = 0404B4\n| body1 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1 = 0404B4\n| shorts1 = 0404B4\n| socks1 = 0404B4\n| pattern_la2 = _coleraine1718a\n| pattern_b2 = _coleraine1718a\n| pattern_ra2 = _coleraine1718a\n| pattern_sh2 = _coleraine1718a\n| pattern_so2 = _coleraine1718a\n| leftarm2 = FF0000\n| body2 = FF0000\n| rightarm2 = FF0000\n| shorts2 = FF0000\n| socks2 = FFFFFF|\n}}\n\n'''Coleraine Football Club''' is a [[Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] semi-professional [[association football|football]] club, playing in the [[NIFL Premiership]]. The club, founded in 1927, hails from [[Coleraine]], County Londonderry and plays its home matches at [[The Showgrounds (Coleraine)|The Showgrounds]]. Club colours are blue and white. The club won the [[NIFL Premiership|Irish League]] title once (in [[1973\u201374 Irish League|1973\u201374]]) and the [[Irish Cup]] on six occasions, most recently in 2017\u201318. They are also the only Irish League club to have won two successive all-Ireland competitions, lifting the [[Blaxnit Cup]] in 1969 and 1970. The club is bitter rivals with [[Ballymena United F.C.|Ballymena United]] with their matches being known as the \"North West Derby\".\n\n==History==\nThe original Coleraine Football Club was founded in June 1927 originally called '''Coleraine FC'''  at a meeting in the local Orange hall. The club was formed out of a merger between two local sides: '''Coleraine Olympic''' and '''Coleraine Alexandra'''. The original club colours were all white, hence the club's original nickname \u2013 the Snowmen. Theyclub secured its first trophy in the 1931\u201332 season, defeating [[Ballymena United F.C.|Ballymena United]] 3\u20130 at [[Solitude (football ground)|Solitude]] to win the [[Gold Cup (Northern Ireland)|Gold Cup]].\n\nIn 1948, Coleraine reached its first [[Irish Cup]] final, going down 3\u20130 to [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]]. 1953 brought another appearance in the final and another defeat, again to Linfield, this time by five goals to nil. The 1950s saw the [[City Cup (Northern Ireland)|City Cup]] won for the first time (1953\u201354) and a second triumph in the [[Gold Cup (Northern Ireland)|Gold Cup]] (1958).\n\nIn 1961, chairman Jack Doherty persuaded [[Bertie Peacock]] to sign for Coleraine after he left [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]. It would prove to be one of the most important transfers in the club's history. In 1965, Coleraine won the [[Irish Cup]] for the first time, defeating [[Glenavon F.C.|Glenavon]] 2\u20131 at [[Windsor Park]], with goals from Shaun Dunlop and Derek Irwin. Coleraine thus gained its first experience of European football, against [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] outfit [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kiev]]. Coleraine also won the first two [[Blaxnit Cup|Blaxnit all-Ireland cup]]s in 1969 and 1970. Coleraine faced [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in the 1970 [[Fairs Cup]], and after a 1\u20131 draw in the first leg, the Bannsiders pulled off an historic 3\u20132 victory thanks to a [[Des Dickson (footballer, born 1948)|Des Dickson]] hat-trick.\n\nIn 1972, the [[Irish Cup]] was won again, this time by beating [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 2\u20131, with goals from Des Dickson and [[Ivan Murray]]. The [[Holy Grail]] of the [[IFA Premiership|Gibson Cup]] was finally captured in 1974. Under the management of Bertie Peacock, the squad consisting of the likes of Des Dickson, Johnny McCurdy, Ivan Murray, Michael Guy and Vince Magee clinched the title ahead of [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]]. Bertie Peacock resigned in 1974 and Ivan Murray and Johnny McCurdy took over the reins. Murray continued as manager until 1978 and during his spell in charge the [[Irish Cup]] was won twice more \u2013 both times against [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]]. In 1975, it took three games before a goal from Jim \"Chang\" Smith in the second replay proved decisive. The 1977 victory was more emphatic with [[Liam Beckett]], Des Dickson, Frankie Moffatt and Michael Guy scoring to give Coleraine a 4\u20131 victory. It was to be the club's last major trophy for 26 years.\n\nIn the 1980s there were two more cup finals, in 1982 and 1986, ending in defeats to [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] and [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]] respectively. For three seasons in a row in the mid-1980s the club finished second in the league behind Linfield, but in the first part of the 1990s Coleraine struggled. In 1995 they dropped into the First Division. Under [[Kenny Shiels]], Coleraine won the inaugural First Division title and in its first season back in the top flight, won the [[Ulster Cup]] and came agonisingly close to the title, being pipped late on by [[Crusaders F.C.|Crusaders]].\n\nAfter a poor start to the 1999\u201300 season, Shiels resigned and was replaced by Marty Quinn, who rallied the team to finish second in the league behind Linfield and reach the Irish Cup semi-finals and the Coca-Cola Cup final. The next 2 seasons saw Coleraine finish fourth both times \u2013 potential title challenges being ruined by inconsistency. In 2002\u201303, Coleraine ended the season in third place and reached their first Irish Cup Final since 1986. In the final, they faced [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]] as massive underdogs as the east Belfast side were looking to complete a clean sweep of trophies. After an early strike from [[Gareth McAuley]] was harshly ruled out, Coleraine kept going and scored through [[Jody Tolan]]. Despite increasing Glentoran pressure, Coleraine held on and the trophy famine was over. The following season saw the club reach the Irish Cup final again, but this time it was Glentoran who emerged triumphant.\n\nThe club's well-publicised financial problems had already overshadowed much of the 2003\u201304 season (despite a substantial donation from ''Cold Feet'' actor and Coleraine fan [[James Nesbitt]]) and at its end the club was forced to operate on a reduced budget, with several top players leaving. Despite this a top six finish was still achieved. The summer of 2005 saw more budget cuts and several big names leaving the Showgrounds, but this time the main concern for fans was the very future of the club. In August, the [[Inland Revenue]] filed for a winding-up order against Coleraine due to debts of \u00a31.3 million. The Friends of Coleraine, worked tirelessly to persuade the High Court to postpone the hearing to allow them to put together a business plan to show that the club could be viably run. The club were liquidated on 9 August 2006 after they were allowed to enter administration, and a steering committee was set up to run the new club Coleraine FC Ltd.\n\nThe club went on to defeat [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] to win the [[North West Senior Cup]] for the 1st time. The club were incredibly allowed to stay in the Premier League and survival was ensured on the pitch, the Friends of Coleraine formally took control of the club and appointed a new board. In 2008 the club reached the Irish Cup final, but lost 2\u20131 to Linfield. Manager Marty Quinn resigned after that game and his successor, former assistant David Platt, led Coleraine to a fifth-place finish in his first season in charge.\n\nOn 27 March 2010, Coleraine narrowly lost on penalties against Glentoran in the final of the [[Northern Irish League Cup|Co-Operative Insurance Cup]]. They also lost out to Linfield in the semi-finals of the Irish Cup. Despite possessing the two top goalscorers in the league, including 41 goal [[Rory Patterson]], Coleraine could only finish the season in seventh. Despite the arrival of much-travelled English striker [[Leon Knight]], inconsistent form throughout the first half of the 2010\u201311 season resulted in manager David Platt being sacked at the start of February. His replacement, Oran Kearney revitalised a struggling team and they climbed the table rapidly, again ending up seventh.\n\nAn overhaul of the squad over the summer saw Kearney put his mark on the club and the improvement shown in his first four months in charge then continued, with Coleraine performing well in the league and reaching the final of the IRN-BRU League Cup.\n\nIn 2012\u201313 Coleraine finished the season in 6th place after making the split five games previously.\n\nIn the 2015\u201316 season, after many average seasons, the Bannsiders hit title winning form, going on a winning run with it being halted after a while by [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]]. They started to fall away after that result, being knocked out of the [[Irish Cup]] by 3\u20131 by [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] and finished in 5th place and lost the Europa League Play-off by 2\u20131 to [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]].\n\nThe 2016\u20132017 was a fairly good one for the Bannsiders with them currently sitting an impressive 3rd in the table and they also booked their place in the 2017 Irish Cup Final by beating [[Glenavon F.C.|Glenavon]] 2\u20131 to reach their first final in nine years, where they lost 3\u20130 to the double winners [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]]. \n\nAt the start of the 2017/18 season 'The Bannsiders' made a few new signings. [[Josh Carson]], who came from Linfield originally playing for York City and Ipswich Town, signed for Coleraine as well as Aaron Traynor and Stephen O'Donnell from Warrenpoint Town and Institute respectively. They started their pre-season off well by beating Bangor City 3\u20131. They were then defeated in the Europa League first round qualifier by Haugesund from Norway. During the 2017/18 season, the Bannsiders went on an amazing run, losing once only to [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] in the [[NIFL Premiership]], finally finishing in second place, two points behind Crusaders. Although Coleraine did not attain the title, a sixth Irish Cup triumph was secured when they defeated Cliftonville in the final of that competition in May, thanks to the heroics of starlet Aaron Burns. \n\nOran Kearney left the club to take over at [[SPFL Premiership]] side [[St. Mirren F.C.|St. Mirren]] in September 2018, and was replaced by [[Dungannon Swifts F.C.|Dungannon Swifts]] manager Rodney McAree, who guided Coleraine to a sixth-place finish and an Irish Cup semi-final. Following a failure to win the Europa League playoffs, McAree was sacked on 10 May 2019, having only been in charge for eight months. Kearney departed St. Mirren via mutual agreement to rejoin Coleraine as manager on 3 July 2019, citing family reasons and a lack of ambition on his part due to full time football being outside his appetite. Kearney settled back into his role as manager of Coleraine for a second spell. The summer transfer window of 19/20 caused some controversy with Kearney allowing star striker Jamie McGonigle to leave for a paltry sum, of \u00a32,000, while Aaron Burns was also allowed to leave for free, despite Kearney spending \u00a320,000 on the winger 18 months previously. \n\nDespite losing their two best players in McGonigle and Burns, Coleraine started the season well, recording notable victories over reigning Champions and runners ups, Linfield and Ballymena respectively. With the club involved in a five way title race, the club opted to bolster their squad in the January window with the club record signing of Nixon from Carrick for \u00a330,000. \n\n==European record==\n{{main|Northern Irish football clubs in European competitions}}\n\n===Overview===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Competition\n! Matches\n! W\n! D\n! L\n! GF\n! GA\n|-\n| [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>11</center>\n|-\n| [[UEFA Europa League|Inter-Cities Fairs Cup / UEFA Cup / UEFA Europa League]]\n| <center>26</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n| <center>17</center>\n| <center>24</center>\n| <center>69</center>\n|-\n| ''[[European Cup Winners' Cup]]''\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>7</center>\n| <center>7</center>\n| <center>34</center>\n|-\n| ''[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]''\n| <center>4</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>9</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n|-\n| '''TOTAL'''\n| <center>'''40'''</center>\n| <center>'''4'''</center>\n| <center>'''8'''</center>\n| <center>'''28'''</center>\n| <center>'''41'''</center>\n| <center>'''120'''</center>\n|}\n\n===Matches===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align: center;\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Opponent\n! Home\n! Away\n! [[Aggregate score|Aggregate]]\n|-\n| [[1965\u201366 European Cup Winners' Cup|1965\u201366]]\n| [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| [[1965\u201366 European Cup Winners' Cup#First round|1R]]\n| align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|Soviet Union}} [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20136\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20134\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\" style=\"text-align:ce